    <!--                  SECTION ONE: VECTORS — BASICS                  -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_13">• A vector is a directed segment with start and end points.
\n • Its length is the distance between those points.
\n • Vectors can be equal, opposite, or null.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does a null vector have length zero? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefQuestion_13">Does a null vector have length equal to zero?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerOne_13">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerTwo_13">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerThree_13"></string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_13">True</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_13">• Vectors add by triangle or parallelogram rule.
\n • Addition is associative and commutative.
\n • Subtraction uses the opposite of a vector.</string>

    <!-- Q: Is vector addition commutative? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsQuestion_13">Is vector addition commutative (i.e. a⃗ + b⃗ = b⃗ + a⃗)?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerOne_13">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_13">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerThree_13"></string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_13">True</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExamples_13">• Commutativity via parallelogram: place a⃗ and b⃗ from the same point O. The parallelogram they span has a diagonal equal to a⃗ + b⃗; since both routes (a⃗ then b⃗, or b⃗ then a⃗) reach the same corner, a⃗ + b⃗ = b⃗ + a⃗.
\n • Vector subtraction a⃗ − b⃗: place both vectors from the same origin; the result is the vector from the tip of b⃗ to the tip of a⃗ — i.e. the vector you add to b⃗ to get a⃗.
\n • The zero vector acts as an identity: a⃗ + 0⃗ = a⃗, and a⃗ + (−a⃗) = 0⃗, confirming the additive inverse property.</string>

    <!-- Q: Vector subtraction a⃗ − b⃗ gives the vector from the tip of b⃗ to the tip of a⃗. Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExQuestion_13">When both vectors share the same origin, does a⃗ − b⃗ point from the tip of b⃗ to the tip of a⃗?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_13">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_13">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_13"></string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_13">True</string>

