    <!--              SECTION TWO: SCALAR MULTIPLICATION OF VECTORS      -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDef_13">• Multiplying a vector by x changes its length.
\n • Direction stays the same for x&gt;0 and reverses for x&lt;0.
\n • Defines scaling of a vector.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does multiplying a vector by a negative scalar reverse its direction? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefQuestion_13">Does multiplying a vector by a negative scalar reverse its direction?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerOne_13">True</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerTwo_13">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerThree_13"></string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_13">True</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryProperties_13">• Vector multiplication follows associative and distributive laws.
\n • Two vectors are collinear if one is a scalar multiple of the other.
\n • Expresses alignment through scalar ratios.</string>

    <!-- Q: Are two vectors collinear if one is a scalar multiple of the other? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsQuestion_13">Are two vectors collinear if and only if one is a scalar multiple of the other?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerOne_13">True</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_13">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerThree_13"></string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_13">True</string>

    <!-- Fixed typo: centroid ratio 13:1 → 2:1 -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExamples_13">• Let M and N be midpoints of sides AB and AC of triangle ABC. Using vectors: MN⃗ = MA⃗ + AN⃗ = −½AB⃗ + ½AC⃗ = ½(AC⃗ − AB⃗) = ½BC⃗, so MN ∥ BC and MN = ½BC — the midline theorem.
\n • Centroid proof: label position vectors of vertices a⃗, b⃗, c⃗. The centroid G has position vector g⃗ = (a⃗ + b⃗ + c⃗)/3. Each median passes through G at 2/3 of its length from the vertex, confirming the centroid divides each median in ratio 2:1.
\n • Scalar multiplication by k = −1 maps every vector to its opposite, which is exactly central symmetry about the origin — linking vector algebra to geometric transformations.</string>

    <!-- Q: The centroid divides each median in ratio from vertex. Answer: 2:1 -->
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExQuestion_13">In what ratio does the centroid divide each median (from vertex to midpoint)?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_13">1:2</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_13">1:1</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_13">2:1</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_13">2:1</string>

