    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryWorkedExamples_13">• Law of Sines example: triangle with a = 8, α = 30°, β = 45°. Then b/sin45° = 8/sin30° = 16, so b = 16 × sin(45°) = 16 × (√2/2) = 8√2.
\n • Law of Cosines example: triangle with b = 5, c = 7, α = 60°. Then a² = 25 + 49 − 2×5×7×cos(60°) = 74 − 70×½ = 74 − 35 = 39, so a = √39.
\n • Parallelogram diagonal rule: if sides are a and b and one angle is α, then the diagonals d1 and d2 satisfy d1² + d2² = 2(a² + b²) — derived by applying the Law of Cosines to both triangles formed by the diagonal.</string>

